{
  "topic": "El Futuro Simple: Describiendo Eventos, Personas y Lugares Futuros",
  "explanation": "The simple future tense (El Futuro Simple) in Spanish is used to talk about actions or states that *will happen* in the future. It's often used for predictions, plans, or simply stating what will be true later on.\n\n**Formation of Regular Verbs:**\nFor most verbs, you form the future tense by adding specific endings directly to the *infinitive* form of the verb (the -ar, -er, or -ir form). The good news is that the endings are the same for all three verb types!\n\n| Subject  | Endings      | Example (Hablar) | Example (Comer) | Example (Vivir) |\n|----------|--------------|------------------|-----------------|-----------------|\n| Yo       | -\u00e9           | hablar\u00e9          | comer\u00e9          | vivir\u00e9          |\n| T\u00fa       | -\u00e1s          | hablar\u00e1s         | comer\u00e1s         | vivir\u00e1s         |\n| \u00c9l/Ella/Ud. | -\u00e1           | hablar\u00e1          | comer\u00e1          | vivir\u00e1          |\n| Nosotros | -emos        | hablaremos        | comeremos       | viviremos       |\n| Vosotros | -\u00e9is         | hablar\u00e9is        | comer\u00e9is        | vivir\u00e9is        |\n| Ellos/Ellas/Uds. | -\u00e1n          | hablar\u00e1n         | comer\u00e1n         | vivir\u00e1n         |\n\n**Irregular Verbs:**\nSome verbs have irregular stems in the future tense, but they still use the same endings. These stems often involve dropping a vowel or adding a 'd'. Here are some common irregular verbs and their future stems:\n\n*   **Decir** (to say) -> dir- (dir\u00e9, dir\u00e1s, etc.)\n*   **Hacer** (to do/make) -> har- (har\u00e9, har\u00e1s, etc.)\n*   **Poder** (to be able to) -> podr- (podr\u00e9, podr\u00e1s, etc.)\n*   **Poner** (to put) -> pondr- (pondr\u00e9, pondr\u00e1s, etc.)\n*   **Querer** (to want) -> querr- (querr\u00e9, querr\u00e1s, etc.)\n*   **Saber** (to know) -> sabr- (sabr\u00e9, sabr\u00e1s, etc.)\n*   **Salir** (to leave/go out) -> saldr- (saldr\u00e9, saldr\u00e1s, etc.)\n*   **Tener** (to have) -> tendr- (tendr\u00e9, tendr\u00e1s, etc.)\n*   **Venir** (to come) -> vendr- (vendr\u00e9, vendr\u00e1s, etc.)\n*   **Haber** (to have/there is) -> habr- (habr\u00e1 - only used in the impersonal 'there will be')\n\n**Describing People and Places in the Future:**\nTo describe what someone or something *will be like* or *will have* in the future, you use the future tense of verbs like *ser*, *estar*, or *tener* followed by an adjective or descriptive phrase. Remember the crucial difference between *ser* (for inherent qualities, permanent states, identity) and *estar* (for temporary states, location, condition)! Using the correct verb is key for accurate descriptions.\n\n*   **Ser\u00e1 / Ser\u00e1n**: Used for describing inherent characteristics, professions, what something/someone will permanently be like, or the nature of an event.\n*   **Estar\u00e1 / Estar\u00e1n**: Used for describing temporary conditions, emotions, or location in the future.\n*   **Tendr\u00e1 / Tendr\u00e1n**: Used for describing what someone/something will possess or experience in the future.",
  "examples": [
    {
      "correct": "Ma\u00f1ana, el clima *ser\u00e1* soleado y *har\u00e1* calor.",
      "translation": "Tomorrow, the weather will be sunny and it will be hot.",
      "explanation": "Uses *ser\u00e1* (future of *ser*) for a weather description (an inherent characteristic of the day) and *har\u00e1* (irregular future of *hacer*) for another weather condition. Both refer to future states."
    },
    {
      "correct": "Mi hermana *ser\u00e1* una gran ingeniera cuando termine sus estudios.",
